    <mxCell id="p4n" parent="1" style="text;html=1;align=left;fontSize=8;fontColor=#555;" value="&lt;b style=&quot;color:#9673a6&quot;&gt;T0 owns 4 patches&lt;/b&gt;, one in each subtile (same position).&#10;regM[WMITER·TM=16], regN[WNITER·TN=8]&#10;threadResults[WMITER·TM·WNITER·TN = 128]" vertex="1"><mxGeometry x="790" y="256" width="250" height="40" as="geometry" /></mxCell>
    <mxCell id="sum" parent="1" style="rounded=1;whiteSpace=wrap;html=1;fillColor=#fef3c7;strokeColor=#b45309;fontSize=10;align=left;verticalAlign=middle;spacingLeft=10;spacingRight=10;" value="&lt;b&gt;Why it looks complicated:&lt;/b&gt; a thread's 128 results are NOT one contiguous patch. The warp tile splits into WMITER×WNITER = 2×2 subtiles; the warp's 32 threads tile each subtile with one 8×4 patch, and the SAME thread reappears in all four. So one thread holds &lt;b&gt;4 patches scattered across the warp tile&lt;/b&gt;. Loading regM/regN once per dotIdx and reusing them across all subtiles is what raises arithmetic intensity at the warp level." vertex="1"><mxGeometry x="20" y="305" width="1010" height="52" as="geometry" /></mxCell>
  </root>
</mxGraphModel>
